<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-116-239 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 194 405</DOCID><JOURNAL>Journal of the Association for Computing Machinery  July 1991 v38n3 p534(25).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Abstraction in query processing.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Imielinski, Tomasz.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Abstractions which lead to computationally simpler deductionprocedures allow simplified automated deduction with large amountsof data.andP;  Incomplete data, such as existentially quantifiedformulas or disjunctions, need to be interpreted as theory in thatthe database state is consistent with integrity restraints.andP;  Achase procedure preserves all positive queries and is anabstraction mapping for them.andP;  Since data dependencies areignored, costly procedures of paramodulation dealing with equalitypredicate are avoided.andP;  For finite procedures similar to chase tobe constructed for restricted tables and data dependencies,hypothetical chase rules would need an arbitrary n and could nothave fixed length.andP;  Globally computing abstraction rather thanlooking at the data base's local parts is a costly procedure.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data Base Management SystemsArtificial IntelligenceDeductive ReasoningQuery Languages.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>